        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">45, Charles Street</hi></placeName>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>How seldom things in this World dove tail in nicely— A wet day and the receipt of your interesting book was, however, all that I could wish<ref target="#foot.f2"/>   I have been reading the Drosera’s with the greatest attention and am going thoroughly to digest every part—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I did so enjoy my afternoon passed with you and M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Darwin and if it were not too much to ask—later on—if it were possible I should so like to come down again<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I leave London about the 6<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of August</p>
<p>Y<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> most obliged | D Nevill <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> July</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref> (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref> was published on 2 July 1875 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)). Nevill’s name is on the presentation list for the book (see Appendix IV).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The first twelve chapters of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref> focused on <hi rend="italic">Drosera</hi> (sundew); the plant’s digestive powers were discussed on pp. 85–135. Nevill had sent CD specimens of <hi rend="italic">D. montana</hi> and other plants (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 22, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9627.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to D. F. Nevill, 7 September 1874</ref>, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4097.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Insectivorous plants</hi></ref>, pp. 281–2 and 431).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Nevill visited the Darwins at Down House on 4 May 1875 (<ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242)).</note>
